commit_message:
Check NFS protocol

Since I896f70d204ad103e968ab242ba9045ca984827c4 Cinder supports
NFS encryption. However, attaching or booting from an NFS
encrypted volume fails with QEMU: The image is not in qcow2
format.

This problem occurs because is_luks() returns false for the NFS
case because NFS uses LUKS inside qcow2 and not regular LUKS.
Therefore, nova formats the volume to native LUKS.

This patch adds a check if the protocol is nfs. If that's the
case the formatting is skipped.

Co-Author-By: Eric Harney <eharney@redhat.com>
Closes-Bug: #1987311
Change-Id: Ia9bc5fab596dadae33f6f208fedd9170d134092b

commit_message:
Triggering overcloud container CLI discovery task on allovercloud group

The overcloud container CLI was previously only discovered if overcloud group
was present in the inventory. As one of the validations targets,
the 'allovercloud' group over took much of the previous 'overcloud' group responsibilities.

This could lead to an edge case when no overcloud container CLI was discovered on overcloud nodes,
and the undercloud cli was never sought. The relevant variable remained
unfilled and caused eventual syntax error during evaluation of a conditional
in the following task.

Resolves: rhbz#2127928

Signed-off-by: Jiri Podivin <jpodivin@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I84a7c20a41698d57a379720ef0424f5220bb9edd
(cherry picked from commit 29ad8ab3421776f906f98fac3f3efcc680a11e11)

[{'created': '2022-02-08 19:40:11.000000000', 'message': 'Revert "Revert resize: wait for events according to hybrid plug"

This reverts commit 7a7a223602ca5aa0aca8f65a6ab143f1d8f8ec1b.

That commit was added because - tl'dr - upon revert resize, Neutron
with the OVS backend and the iptables security group driver would send
us the network-vif-plugged event as soon as we updated the port
binding.

That behaviour has changed with commit 66c7f00e1d9. With that commit,
we started unplugging the vifs on the source compute host when doing a
resize. When reverting the resize, the vifs had to be re-plugged again,
regarldess of the networking backend in use. This renders commit
7a7a223602ca5aa0aca8f65a6ab143f1d8f8ec1b. pointless, and it can be
reverted.

Conflicts - most have to do with context around this commit's code:

nova/compute/manager.py

    a2984b647a4 added provider_mappings to
    _finish_revert_resize_network_migrate_finish()'s signature

    750aef54b19 started using
    _finish_revert_resize_network_migrate_finish() in
    _finish_revert_snapshot_based_resize_at_source()

nova/network/model.py

    8b33ac06445 added get_live_migration_plug_time_events() and
    has_live_migration_plug_time_event()

    7da94440db1 added has_port_with_allocation()

nova/objects/migration.py

    f203da38387 added is_resize() and is_live_migration()

nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute.py

    a0e60feb3ec added request_spec to the test

nova/tests/unit/compute/test_compute_mgr.py

    be278006a58 added unit tests below ours

nova/tests/unit/network/test_network_info.py

    7da94440db1 (again) added tests for has_port_with_allocation()

nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py and
nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py are different in that attempting to
identify individual conflicts is a pointless exercise, as so much has
changed (mdev, vtmp, the recent wait for events during hard reboot
workaround config option, etc). They can be treated as
manual removal of any code that had to do with the bind-time events
logic (though guided by the conflict markers in git).

TODO(artom) There was a follow up commit,
78a08d44ea68b31e27ce344f452756886ad309bd, that added the migration
parameter to finish_revert_migration(). This is no longer needed, as
the migration was only used to obtain plug-time events. We'll have to
undo that as well.

commit_message:
Revert "Revert resize: wait for events according to hybrid plug"

This reverts commit 7a7a223602ca5aa0aca8f65a6ab143f1d8f8ec1b.

That commit was added because - tl'dr - upon revert resize, Neutron
with the OVS backend and the iptables security group driver would send
us the network-vif-plugged event as soon as we updated the port
binding.

That behaviour has changed with commit 66c7f00e1d9. With that commit,
we started unplugging the vifs on the source compute host when doing a
resize. When reverting the resize, the vifs had to be re-plugged again,
regarldess of the networking backend in use. This renders commit
7a7a223602ca5aa0aca8f65a6ab143f1d8f8ec1b. pointless, and it can be
reverted.

Backport is clean from master, and the TODO that was present in the
commit message on master is removed, as its a driver interface change
and can only be done on master.

Closes-bug: 1952003
Change-Id: I3cb39a9ec2c260f422b3c48122b9db512cdd799b
(cherry picked from commit 0b0f40d1b308b29da537859b72080488560c23d4)
(cherry picked from commit c3ebe0f39e82cf1df6886cfd03fd8de62548fb26)

commit_message:
Add nova-ovs-hybrid-plug job

We have a gap in our testing of the exernal events interaction between
Nova and Neutron. The nova-next job tests with the OVS network
backend, and Neutron has jobs that test the OVN network backend, but
nothing tests OVS + the iptables security group firewall driver, aka
"hybrid plug". Add a job to test that.

Conflicts in .zuul.yaml due to efd28166191 which added the
nova-live-migration-ceph job roughly where this patch adds
nova-ovs-hybrid-plug.

Also had to change the nova-base-irrelevant-files reference to
dsvm-irrelevant-files, as the former hasn't been introduced in
wallaby.

Related-bug: 1952003
Change-Id: Ie42eaa2a39ef097b0eb69b8863bb342bae007fff
(cherry picked from commit ded6168ad729e747fc976ca3cdb8baf971fbc31a)
(cherry picked from commit b414fe18f1a9a688a0291e97eb00e3ce3b2f4a52)

commit_message:
Fix unplugging VIF when migrate/resize VM

When migrating/resizing VM to destination
host that has VIF type difference from source VIF
type, it fails due to exception in unplugging
VIF on source host after user perform a confirmation
action.

This change unplugs the vifs in resize_instance and
wraps the call to unplug in confirm with an try except
block. the call to unplug_vifs in confirm is not removed
to support rolling upgrades but a todo is added to remove
it after the Wallaby release.

Change-Id: I2c195df5fcf844c0587933b5b5995bdca1a3ebed
Closes-Bug: #1895220
(cherry picked from commit 66c7f00e1d9d7c0eebe46eb4b24b2b21f7413789)
(cherry picked from commit 95614f600bdc09c2c96ca61a6e7e5d66cc93e9d7)
    Conflicts:
        nova/tests/unit/virt/libvirt/test_driver.py

commit_message:
zuul: new LVM/nvmet job

Non voting because the feature has known issue and there
are a few patches floating around.
The job does not test cinderlib integration because
cinderlib does not support NVMe yet at this point.

At the same time, switch to the new devstack variable
for targets in all jobs.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/devstack/+/814193
Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/cinder/+/843493
Change-Id: I3f8cc73730ad2c74e0c2cf43243e7657f02fbd28

commit_message:
Restoring logging facility and implementing default logger

The logging statements in our modules, including CLI, are now
using a dedicated VF logger with Syslog and stdout handlers.

This will ensure, that all messages will be properly journaled
and that only messages >warn will be displayed to user by default.
Patch only changes behavior of the logging statements in the VF
code itself. Log statements in imported modules, such as ansible-runner,
will behave as before.

In the absence of available '/dev/log' device the user will be notified,
during logger init, by a warning level message.

Tests for the new code are included.

Signed-off-by: Jiri Podivin <jpodivin@redhat.com>
Change-Id: If8ed6510dad16dc8495717789bb132b957828e0d

commit_message:
Eliminate unnecessary role looping in deploy-steps.j2

These role task inclusions force a linear-like sequence
and result in a lot of unnecessary skipped tasks. This
takes extra time, and causes a lot of log noise which
makes debugging more difficult.

Given that a host can ever only have a single role, it
makes more sense to just include the applicable role
task file if it exists.

Change-Id: Id2cadceaaf563dc94fcf2d8ce0f0cb9054a65d40

commit_message:
Respect constraints on tempest venv consistently

In case of online mode, there is a procedure to recreate tempest venv.
For consistency of tempest venv during the entire stack.sh process,
add logic to consider the TEMPEST_VENV_UPPER_CONSTRAINTS option here.

Closes-bug: #1980483
Signed-off-by: June Yi <june.yi@samsung.com>
Change-Id: I0cea282152fd363af8671cab1b5f733ebe2bd4df
(cherry picked from commit b9b6d6b862ce69a875c152ad30da8f4717c75272)

commit_message:
Specify number of threads for designate bind9 backend

Bind9 is running without limit for UDP listeners.
This patch is changing this behaviour and sets max 32
of UDP listeners. This is needed because of bug below [1].

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/bind9/+bug/1827923

Change-Id: Ie4c2ac4d5e990ebdc30c3a94d855703d814f1fee

commit_message:
Specify number of threads for designate bind9 backend

Bind9 is running without limit for UDP listeners.
This patch is changing this behaviour and sets max 32
of UDP listeners. This is needed because of bug below [1].

[1] https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu/+source/bind9/+bug/1827923

Change-Id: Ie4c2ac4d5e990ebdc30c3a94d855703d814f1fee

commit_message:
Fix unplugging VIF when migrate/resize VM

When migrating/resizing VM to destination
host that has VIF type difference from source VIF
type, it fails due to exception in unplugging
VIF on source host after user perform a confirmation
action.

This change unplugs the vifs in resize_instance and
wraps the call to unplug in confirm with an try except
block. the call to unplug_vifs in confirm is not removed
to support rolling upgrades but a todo is added to remove
it after the Wallaby release.

Change-Id: I2c195df5fcf844c0587933b5b5995bdca1a3ebed
Closes-Bug: #1895220
(cherry picked from commit 66c7f00e1d9d7c0eebe46eb4b24b2b21f7413789)

[{'created': '2022-02-21 19:45:33.000000000', 'message': 'Update of OVN controllers as an external task.

OVN requires ovn_controller to be updated before ovn_northd.

This implement a new step in the update process to be run before
"overcloud update run ..." commands and after "overcloud update
prepare".

Running[1]:

  openstack overcloud external-update run --stack qe-Cloud-0 --tags ovn

triggers an update of the ovn_controller containers on every
server in parallel.

We don't add the whole configuration of the ovn_controller here,
meaning we *don't* run puppet for the new ovn_controller. Maybe this
should be added as an option, but the time taken by this step will
increase. Current testing show that it's not mandatary to have a
successful update.

Note that new configuration will be taken into account later during
the "update run" commands.

By doing this we avoid any issues where a discrepency in version
between ovn-northd and ovn-controller would cause a cut in the
data-plane.

commit_message:
Update of OVN controllers as an external task.

OVN requires ovn_controller to be updated before ovn_northd.

This implement a new step in the update process to be run before
"overcloud update run ..." commands and after "overcloud update
prepare".

Running:

  openstack overcloud external-update run --stack qe-Cloud-0 --tags ovn

triggers an update of the ovn_controller containers on every
server in parallel.

We don't add the whole configuration of the ovn_controller here,
meaning we *don't* run puppet for the new ovn_controller. Maybe this
should be added as an option, but the time taken by this step will
increase. Current testing show that it's not mandatary to have a
successful update.

Note that new configuration will be taken into account later during
the "update run" commands.

By doing this we avoid any issues where a discrepency in version
between ovn-northd and ovn-controller would cause a cut in the
data-plane.

Change-Id: Icc58fa5f3ccfea9b12154629be977504fe97b45f

commit_message:
Change the unique properties of secret consumers

This makes the resource_id unique together with
service and resource_type (in addition to secret_id).
Additionaly the auto-generated alembic migration also
adds the missing foreign key for project_id.

Change-Id: I5ff1760451fa84784fd8b84fb9c5889e56350422

commit_message:
Fix charmcraft 2.0/stable on launchpad

The build log for the charm on launchpad ends up with src already
existing which means that the mkdir failed.  Change it to a mkdir -p src
and just touch/make the file executable to try to change anything that
might be there.

Change-Id: I4e5459b6d6ff1bf4690ba635b87947594ce5fb12

[{'created': '2022-09-16 14:05:03.000000000', 'message': '[NetApp] Fix non-disruptive migration cifs shares

Migrate non-disruptive cifs share from different pools change the
export location. When the non-disruptive migration complete
process is started a new share and export location is created. As
result, Manila finds a conflict between the old export location and
the new one.

This patch is adding a parameter that identifies if a migration
process is in progress and skip the creation of a new share, also
change the way that the export location is created. Instead of
create the export path with share name, the new one is taken from
the backend.

Change-Id: I1bb888a0b644f0b071816d275d464c4dd27125a7
Co-authored-by: Lucas Oliveira <lucasmoliveira059@gmail.com>
Closes-bug: #1920937

commit_message:
[NetApp] Fix non-disruptive migration cifs shares

Migrate non-disruptive cifs share from different pools change the
export location. When the non-disruptive migration complete
process is started a new share and export location is created. As
result, Manila finds a conflict between the old export location and
the new one.

This patch add a condition to skip export location creation when
a CIFS migration is in progress, also change the way that the export
location is created. Instead of create the export path with share
name, the new one is taken from the backend.

Change-Id: I1bb888a0b644f0b071816d275d464c4dd27125a7
Co-authored-by: Lucas Oliveira <lucasmoliveira059@gmail.com>
Closes-bug: #1920937

subject: Limit ResourceGroup Concurrency
messages:
[{'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-05-27 10:00:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-05-27 11:42:31.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-05-27 12:09:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-09-05 05:14:38.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-09-05 05:15:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 27427, 'date': '2019-09-06 13:11:08.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm interested in this idea Rabi.

Can you tell me if the plan is to expose this fake dependency limit through a configuration variable?  If this is an effective method to limit the size of the message queue, I can see operators needing to tweak this."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-09-16 11:12:26.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: -Workflow

> Can you tell me if the plan is to expose this fake dependency limit through a configuration variable?

We limit concurrency to the number of workers available, which is linked to a configuration (num_engine_workers). Though it may not be very effective, if you've large number of RGs in your stack, it would surely reduce the concurrency in large RGs. I've seen this reducing total memory usage by 30% when deploying more than 500+ nodes in my tests."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-09-16 11:13:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Commit message was updated.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2019-09-17 01:40:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

This is less scary than it could be, given that it is confined to these particular resource types. In the past we have had proposals to do similar things in every stack stack. My proposed alternative was https://review.opendev.org/301323 but it was only for legacy and doesn't have any obvious equivalent in convergence. (The thing I liked about it was that it was self-tuning, in the sense that it didn't need to make any assumptions about how much CPU each resource used.)

I do think the limits you're imposing here are *way* too low though. How many software deployments can we afford to concurrently wait for? A lot. A lot more than one per worker. Same for creating Nova servers. But for nested stacks, it depends on the contents of the stack.

Suddenly imposing a very low limit on concurrency will inevitably break people whose templates are working for them right now. There's a strong case for setting a high default and making it a configuration option so that TripleO (which involves a large number of deeply-nested stacks in ResourceGroups) can tune it downwards if necessary.

It would be great if we could come up with some sort of alternative that was also self-tuning. In theory the limited number of worker threads in the threadpool was supposed to apply the necessary backpressure, leaving resource check requests in the Rabbit queue if there were no worker threads available to fulfill them. That theory appears to have failed though and I'm not sure why - it seems clear that if we're contemplating patches like this then the thread pools are too large, but I don't know if that's because making them smaller caused more performance issues than it solved or if things are actually broken when there are messages in the queue that we don't have free worker threads to process right now."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-09-17 04:55:39.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

(1 comment)

> I do think the limits you're imposing here are *way* too low though. 

We really don't know what would be the best default, as it would depend on the stack i.e. How many RGs, nested depth and complexity of the group resource stacks etc. I've gone for this, as we've the same for ResourceChain and we've seen it makes a difference in memory usage. IMO, our objective should probably be to allow users to deploy complex stacks with mimumum CPU/RAM requirements. At present it's the exact opposite, as the complexity of the stack increases you need more physical resources for heat-engine, else you can't do any stack operation. Level of concurrency should be a user choice and not the other way around and should just impact the time to complete a stack operation. But, I know it's easier said than done.

> Suddenly imposing a very low limit on concurrency will inevitably break people whose templates are working for them right now.

Not sure I understand why it would break them. It would only more time to complete a stack operation I guess.

> I don't know if that's because making them smaller caused more performance issues than it solved

So with deeply nested stacks, with less number of executor threads, I've seen that you end up with no threads to pick up messages for leaf resources and the whole operation just times out."}, {'account_id': 8833, 'date': '2019-09-17 07:38:25.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2019-09-19 02:52:43.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

recheck'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2019-10-18 21:23:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

> We really don't know what would be the best default, as it would depend on the stack i.e. How many RGs, nested depth and complexity of the group resource stacks etc. I've gone for this, as we've the same for ResourceChain and we've seen it makes a difference in memory usage. IMO, our objective should probably be to allow users to deploy complex stacks with mimumum CPU/RAM requirements. At present it's the exact opposite, as the complexity of the stack increases you need more physical resources for heat-engine, else you can't do any stack operation. Level of concurrency should be a user choice and not the other way around and should just impact the time to complete a stack operation. But, I know it's easier said than done.

Yeah, a backpressure-based solution would be ideal because it doesn't rely on assumptions about what the contents of the stack are. But I don't have any great ideas for how to implement that in convergence.

In this case though, we know that e.g. updating software deployments is cheap, so there is no real reason to apply this to SoftwareDeploymentGroup. Going further, we could even say there's no need to do this in ResourceGroup when the scaled unit is a native resource type (i.e. we would only limit it when the scaled unit is a template resource).

Looking at the original issue from the commit message, the problem is caused by timeouts on the message bus. The worker bus can't timeout because it uses cast, so this must be caused by an excess of requests on the engine bus - of which by far the most expensive thing is validating nested stacks. So how this actually works is specifically by limiting the concurrent updates of nested stacks.

Limiting it to nested stacks would resolve most of the problems, but I still think it would be wise to default to slightly more generous levels of concurrency and perhaps make it configurable for TripleO.

> > Suddenly imposing a very low limit on concurrency will inevitably break people whose templates are working for them right now.

> Not sure I understand why it would break them. It would only more time to complete a stack operation I guess.

It will cause some stacks to start timing out that previously wouldn't have.

> So with deeply nested stacks, with less number of executor threads, I've seen that you end up with no threads to pick up messages for leaf resources and the whole operation just times out.

That's interesting, thanks. This is somewhat surprising - after all, the messages are sent to the queue in a strictly topological sort order... and that applies to the graph of all of the resources in all of the stacks in the tree, so in theory if the queue is behaving as a literal queue then a lack of workers can't cause a deadlock. For a given level of memory use then it shouldn't be slower than this patch, for example. I can see that it would tend more toward a breadth-first traversal where this patch forces it to be more depth-first, but I wouldn't expect any overall time difference.

For replacements and retriggers, a resource that was ready for processing gets sent to the back of the queue which, though it again shouldn't cause a deadlock, could certainly cause extensive delays. I wonder if this contributed to the issues you saw, and whether it's possible to implement some sort of priority queue (could be just a second queue that gets first pick from the thread pool somehow) to get around it."}, {'account_id': 27427, 'date': '2022-09-27 13:06:21.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer <GERRIT_ACCOUNT_27427>.'}]

commit_message:
Limit ResourceGroup Concurrency

In convergence heat, if there are large number of resources
in a group, they are processed concurrently and with limited
number of workers, it can result in large message queue length
and messages timing out. Limit the concurrency by adding
fake dependencies.

Change-Id: I3a9cb7738e7286767bc7f4410b8e3de940f417a8

(1 comment)

No way are we changing existing behaviour, but I would totally support making this configurable - for now at least internally so that different resource types (and I know STX has a bunch of custom autoscaling groups) can make different choices.

Long term, it'd be nice to allow resource types to make sophisticated decisions along the lines of https://docs.aws.amazon.com/autoscaling/ec2/userguide/as-instance-termination.html and make them customisable by the user. For that reason I'd suggest that the change take the form of a custom sort function that can optionally be passed to some API (I don't have a clear idea of which yet)."}, {'account_id': 22776, 'date': '2018-08-03 21:05:41.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

The main reason for this change was to allow the custom naming to be meaningful.
 
If you have VM-0, VM-1 and the oldest is deleted you end up with VM-1.
Next time it scaled up, the size of the group and/or index is meaningless for naming the next VM that is created.  You would end up with  VM-1, VM-1

commit_message:
AutoScale downscale/replace will now support custom sorting options.

grouputils get_member_definitions will now have the option of
choosing custom sorting, by passing the desired list of sorting
criteria. While creating template to downscale/replace, users can
choose what instances should be replace/removed first by passing
sort_keys to get their desired list of old_resources to be passed
into template.member_definitons.

Custom sorting will be optional/configurable, keeping the default
behaviour as it is.

Change-Id: I126874622b8928d859d6d7bd2e10c9c27a156ba5
Story: 2003123
Task: 23243

commit_message:
Refactor for deployed server and nova server

This changes:
1. put the common properties of nova server and
   depolyed server to server_base.py
2. remove handle_delete() of nova server
3. add the support status for OS::Heat::DeployedServer

Change-Id: I80029ff3b83989b9c82ba886eb7b7058fb484c21

commit_message:
Add validation for creation subnet and subnetpools at the same time

When creating a subnet you could not add a cidr and a range before even
if you were creating a subnetpool with that range because heat and
neutron would assume a dynamic pool. with this new validation if a
pool is there and the range is right the creation can continue.

Change-Id: I0a26e39807cbf19bf567301d0367387473623063
Story: #2007985

> I think I understand what you're doing here, but have you confirmed
 > with upstream documentation that this default is unintentional?
 > 
 > Thanks,
 > David

Thanks a lot for your review.
Now I  explain why i modify it.
if we do not set the parameter router of the firewall,it will automatically fill in all the routers of the project when it is created, which is very easy to make mistakes, because  some of the routers may have been associated with a firewall, the new firewall will fail to be added."}, {'account_id': 27427, 'date': '2019-09-13 16:11:53.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Thanks for the help with the explanation. :-)'}, {'account_id': 28543, 'date': '2019-09-14 01:03:11.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 28935, 'date': '2019-09-14 12:17:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 24245, 'date': '2019-09-16 01:38:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

I'm not going to downvote. But I think it would be better to fix this in neutron-fwaas.

I belive catching the FirewallRouterInUse exception here[1], and then remove the router_ids which already have a firewall association before returning the remaining router_ids.

By doing so the firewall is associated with all the tenant routers that do not already have firewall associated, which is closer to the initial behavior which always associated with all routers, see[2].


[1] https://opendev.org/openstack/neutron-fwaas/src/branch/stable/rocky/neutron_fwaas/services/firewall/fwaas_plugin.py#L251
[2] https://opendev.org/openstack/neutron-fwaas/commit/d0704f056021b235caba1f906b1733f422ce68c1"}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2021-03-11 17:35:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

tend to agree with Harald Jensås. also we should not change the default just because it's hard to config. What we should do is to provide better document for this and let people know about this"}, {'account_id': 12404, 'date': '2021-03-11 17:51:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review-2'}, {'account_id': 27427, 'date': '2022-09-27 13:04:19.000000000', 'content': 'Removed reviewer <GERRIT_ACCOUNT_27427> with the following votes:

commit_message:
Modify the process of creating firewall by HOT

I used HOT template to create firewall unsuccessfully.
The reason is that if we do not set the parameter router of the firewall,
it will automatically fill in all the routers of the project when it is
created, which is very easy to make mistakes.So we should modify the process
of creating firewall by HOT.

Change-Id: I11fcb752227c0601bd8c2ff07306b4a4710b63d5
Story: #2006488
Task: #3643

Support to specify 'tag' when attach volume

Nova support to attach volume with 'tag' since
microversion 2.49, this change will support the
function in heat.

commit_message:
Supports 'virtio-forwarder' vnic type for port

Supports the 'virtio-forwarder' vnic type for port sync with Neutron.
The 'virtio-forwarder' is an indirect mode for SR-IOV interfaces used to
connect the instances into the Neutron networks. It has been supported
since the Queens release:
I28315fb12f62dc7d52d099c211086b2b81eca39a

Note that 'virtio-forwarder' is already supported by Horizon:
openstack_dashboard/api/neutron.py:
  ('virtio-forwarder', _('Virtio Forwarder'))

Nova:
nova/network/model.py:
  VNIC_TYPE_VIRTIO_FORWARDER = 'virtio-forwarder'

openstackclient:
openstackclient/network/v2/port.py:
  choices=(...), virtio-forwarder

neutron-lib:
neutron_lib/api/definitions/portbindings.py
  VNIC_VIRTIO_FORWARDER = 'virtio-forwarder'

Task: 40435
Change-Id: Ie65f8858d6d1a1854702eb33c40ea827505bfe51
(cherry picked from commit 03ab18d4599183d13dceb6d1130358f717197136)

Supports the 'virtio-forwarder' vnic type for port sync with Neutron.
The 'virtio-forwarder' is an indirect mode for SR-IOV interfaces used to

  ('virtio-forwarder', _('Virtio Forwarder'))

Nova:

  choices=(...), virtio-forwarder

commit_message:
Allow all packet state for selected ironic services

With nftables, we drop all types of connection
that don't have any "accept" rule.
This is a change compared to the current iptables,
where we drop only the NEW ones. We detected some
of the ironic connections as SYN and/or ACK only, and
they were dropped.
We can see such drops in the hackmd set to track the
nftables switch[1].

[1] https://hackmd.io/F0W2gYw_SiaiWkowjFU9cw

Change-Id: I97e24d6eab8944193c7ce458ec2e45d9e37571cb

commit_message:
Drop DeployedServer resources

We replace the 'deploy_server_id' of TripleOSoftwareDeployment
resources with the actual server_id during config download.
We can manage without creating these DeployedServer resources,
as we don't expect these resources to be SIGNALED.

Change-Id: Ib95a51f0c57943cf6127640b829c042a14d1dcf9

commit_message:
Don't ignore the remaining apt-get update errors

Follow-up to I5ce2eb66a647e1805f086aa37942bf5d13eb4106

So far, I have only observed these causing weird errors later but,
in theory, ignoring these could allow the rest of the code to use
archival (so wrong) entries.

Change-Id: I9cef5ceeb78d431ca232c7b196c48eef5d2ccbca

commit_message:
Add @timestamp filed to subunit documents

To be able to search for test results by the date we need @timestamp
field which contains the exact time of the test execution.

This patch also updates unit tests to reflect the changes.

Change-Id: I7562048528244fbb295687d78063cc28ec4b24fe

commit_message:
[SVf]: mkhost failure when volume and node are on different iogrp

Attach operation fails when volume and back-end host are on different
iogroup. The assignment of the node IP addresses is done outside the
try block, and the "for ip_data in lsip_resp" loop. Because of this
the loop was not consistent before, so only latest node was detected
instead of all nodes.

Closes-Bug: #1985065
Change-Id: I72074357140e9817eee704b6e9ebfd7f50343235

commit_message:
db: Drop redundant indexes on instances and console_auth_tokens tables

 * There were two unique constrains on the same column uuid of instances.
   This change drops one of them. The second constraint was introduced with
   https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/nova/+/97946, but was pending cleanup
   since.
 * In console_auth_tokens there was a unique constraint and another index on
   column token_hash.

Closes-Bug: #1641185
Change-Id: I0ffa47d2afbfbfa63651991b3791dfad3e1832e1

commit_message:
grafana: ignore SHA1 gpg key on CentOS Stream 9 (and family)

https://github.com/grafana/grafana/issues/41036

commit_message:
fix: remove tags filter in the instance list page

Remove tags filter in the instance list page, because the api has not
supported it, this affects:
1. the instance list page
2. the instance list tab in the server group detail page
3. the instance list tab in the host detail page
4. the instance list tab in the flavor detail page

Closes-Bug: #1990826
Change-Id: I400d53d0c051ffab12478796ba0cdc165347ddd4
(cherry picked from commit 1cdecff67922188f5d9c029a8e95cd634fa9105a)

commit_message:
Add healthcheck http url

Ops healthchecks consider check as UP only for 2xx
status codes and the default healthcheck http url
set in ops-sunbeam library localhost:5000 will
return 3xx code due to redirects.
Update the healthcheck http url with localhost:5000/v3

Change-Id: Ia4b9dfd049197e5f2e7f821bdae84f24bff443d9

commit_message:
Spec folder for 2023.1 cycle

Using release number here. In Zed cycle, TC passed
a resolution[1] and updated the release Identification
document[2] to use the release number as primary
identifier in the development cycle. Release name will
be used in marketting and release team tooling (until they
are migrated to work with release number) only.

Let's use release number consistently across OpenStack
projects.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/resolutions/20220524-release-identification-process.html
[2] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/release-naming.html

Change-Id: Ibaeb8c32805e3136ee5947f2527c0d498aeeb7bf

commit_message:
Add a new option for the vhost

We can now specify different Location, with a subset of options. This
will be needed for some of the service vhost, such as Keystone[1].

The layout is pretty simple:
tripleo_httpd_vhost_locations:
  '/my/location':
    - optionName: value
    - optionName2: value2
    - ...

Of course, a new molecule scenario has been added in order to ensure
this new feature is working properly.

[1] https://docs.openstack.org/keystone/yoga/admin/federation/configure_federation.html#configuring-an-httpd-auth-module

Change-Id: I553c1890864f63a32f23d9914df5490ed2577ecb

commit_message:
Make functional tests use stestr instead of nose

This moves in the direction that most projects have been moving
and it works on python 3 too.

Change-Id: I471f803c62722aa9935713921db27fca34282fb5

commit_message:
Check the service status during bootstrap against the internal VIP

This change brings the keystone role into line with others such
as cinder which check the service status using the loadbalancer.

This is useful in environments using a proxy server where the
internal VIP can be included in "no_proxy" but the service IP
for the containers are too numerous to list in "no_proxy" and
stay within the 1024 character limit for pam_env.

Change-Id: I1a4aec40618237aa23b4f40b335c141071a56f08
(cherry picked from commit 05c64f7651a93bfa987a939fce680c3d4b13df30)

commit_message:
feat: Add error message when create instance quota exceeded

Show error message when create instance with quota exceeded:
1. change the instance number
2. change the volume type
3. change the volume size
the above situations may trigger a prompt

Update error message style in the footer

Change-Id: I038bb1919d05d78fc8a78b3ab1a6e72cf327f2ce

commit_message:
feat: Add volume quota when create instance

1. Add volume quota when create instance
2. Quota info support line/ring/table display
3. Remove agent add router e2e check, because sometimes the interface removes the router from one agent successfully, but in fact the route is still in the agent

Change-Id: I161fec1bcd7b8704666c66e3a11168d806c57744

[{'created': '2022-04-05 14:57:10.000000000', 'message': "[WIP] Move to CentOS Stream 9

support SHA1).

needs renaming to be done. For now repos.yaml says 'powertools == crb'
to keep backward compatibility.

'hacluster' repo is now 'resilientstorage' - sorted out in repos.yaml
for now.

"}, {'created': '2022-07-19 12:49:44.000000000', 'message': "Move to CentOS Stream 9

OpenStack 'zed' requires Python 3.8+ so RHEL 8 family has to go.

This changeset moves to CentOS Stream 9 while move to RockyLinux 9 is
planned as final solution.

Some changes in RHEL 9 forced changes in Kolla images:

- ipset/iptables are deprecated so we do not install them for Neutron
- xinetd is not available - we should use systemd instead
  - this can be solved by abandoning use of 'dumb-init'

CI moved to CentOS Stream 9 nodes. Most of K-A jobs disabled.

TODO (both kolla and kolla-ansible):
- add mariadb-clustercheck systemd code in k-a
- document forced disablement of dumb-init
- re-enable non-CentOS CI jobs

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/kolla-ansible/+/839715

Change-Id: I113b9984294cf8663d3fc0c8840320e1d40ea731

commit_message:
Move to CentOS Stream 9

OpenStack 'zed' requires Python 3.8+ so RHEL 8 family has to go.

This changeset moves to CentOS Stream 9 while move to RockyLinux 9 is
planned as final solution.

CI moved to CentOS Stream 9 nodes.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/kolla-ansible/+/839715

Change-Id: I113b9984294cf8663d3fc0c8840320e1d40ea731

specific too allow for role based overrides.

commit_message:
Role specific container support

We may want to be able to specific different containers at a role level.
This requires switching the container image parameters to be role
specific too allow for role based overrides.

Conflicts:
	deployment/frr/frr-container-ansible.yaml
	deployment/ironic/ironic-pxe-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/metrics/qdr-container-ansible.yaml
	deployment/metrics/qdr-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/neutron/neutron-l2gw-api-container-puppet.yaml
	deployment/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-messaging-notify-pacemaker-puppet.yaml
	deployment/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-messaging-pacemaker-puppet.yaml
	deployment/rabbitmq/rabbitmq-messaging-rpc-pacemaker-puppet.yaml

Change-Id: I4090e889a32abd51e7c11139737a7a18e27d18e7
(cherry picked from commit ebab335f3826eabb8d3ec4434cc6d010a4ff453a)

commit_message:
[RBAC] Return 404 if share is inaccessible

When a user is prevented from listing a non-public
share, the API service would return a 403 Forbidden.
This isn't consistent with the API SIG's guidance
on resources restricted by virtue of RBAC policy since
users with malicious intent may use the signal to
mean that the resource exists.

Depends-On: I27fdd7dfffeb15965b66dbb3f6b1568c11ff9ad4
Change-Id: I7e05dcb343c932cc7fec8d395919053d0a1801ce
Closes-Bug: #1901210
Signed-off-by: Goutham Pacha Ravi <gouthampravi@gmail.com>

commit_message:
fix: remove tags filter in the instance list page

Remove tags filter in the instance list page, because the api has not
supported it, this affects:
1. the instance list page
2. the instance list tab in the server group detail page
3. the instance list tab in the host detail page
4. the instance list tab in the flavor detail page

Closes-Bug: #1990826
Change-Id: I400d53d0c051ffab12478796ba0cdc165347ddd4

commit_message:
Do not reboot into nowhere after BIOS settings with fast-track

Currently, the prepare_ramdisk implementation of the
redfish-virtual-media boot interface skips configuring an ISO in
fast-track mode. When rebooting after BIOS/RAID settings changes, we
need to enforce the correct ISO configuration.

Conflicts:
	ironic/drivers/modules/deploy_utils.py
	ironic/drivers/modules/redfish/bios.py

Change-Id: Ibdfe0775065f3b27478305dd18929a291df3ee3c
(cherry picked from commit 89f421b166915a22626dcb919382ce13f4588973)
(cherry picked from commit d85d7f8ac52f289b7b01096c65757b68791f4bd4)
(cherry picked from commit 66373aadc04974de0838abc43c5f9cf113781f1f)

commit_message:
Send the correct location URI to the Glance v2 API

When uploading a volume to an image, send the new-style
cinder://<store-id>/<volume-id> URL to the Glance API if
image_service:store_id is present in the volume type extra specs.

Closes-Bug: #1978020
Co-Authored-By: Rajat Dhasmana <rajatdhasmana@gmail.com>
Change-Id: I815706f691a7d1e5a0c54eb15222417008ef1f34

commit_message:
tests: Enable SQLAlchemy 2.0 deprecation warnings

Well, sort of. We enable them but immediately filter out the ones we're
actually seeing, the rationale being that we can address these in a
piecemeal fashion without the risk of introducing new issues.

There's a lot more to be done here. However, the work done in oslo.db
[1] should provide a guide for how to resolve the outstanding issues.

[1] https://review.opendev.org/q/topic:"sqlalchemy-20"+project:openstack/oslo.db

Change-Id: If8fc919d4a04325ca48a037c02481d9efe54279f
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <sfinucan@redhat.com>

[{'created': '2022-02-10 22:30:35.000000000', 'message': 'Prepare unit test request contexts for secure RBAC

Consolidate the request contexts used in unit tests in places where
the context will be affected by upcoming changes for secure RBAC.
This is mostly in API unit tests, where the test triggers a policy
check. The contexts currently rely on passing the deprecated "owner"
rule, which simply checks the project_id. However, these contexts
do not contain a list of roles, and therefore the policy check will
fail when the "owner" rule is removed in yoga.

The patch contains two components:
1. Eliminate locally declared context objects when an equivalent
   context already exists. For example, many test classes provide
   a "ctxt" attribute, and tests in that class simply need to
   refer to self.ctxt rather than creating another one locally.
2. Context objects are obtained by calling unit test utility
   functions instead of directly instantiating context.RequestContext
   objects. This consolidates where the contexts are created, and
   therefore helps control /how/ they get created.

The new utility functions ensure the contexts contain the appropriate
list of roles, which will allow the unit tests to pass after the
deprecated "owner" rule is removed. Having things consolidated will
also facilitate future changes for secure RBAC, such as when scope
based rules are introduced.

Change-Id: I36e457aa978a968db542e77b15f9b6f4c58677bd

commit_message:
Prepare unit test request contexts for secure RBAC

Consolidate the request contexts used in unit tests in places where
the context will be affected by upcoming changes for secure RBAC.
This is mostly in API unit tests, where the test triggers a policy
check. The contexts currently rely on passing the deprecated "owner"
rule, which simply checks the project_id. However, these contexts
do not contain a list of roles, and therefore the policy check will
fail when the "owner" rule is removed in zed.

The patch contains two components:
1. Eliminate locally declared context objects when an equivalent
   context already exists. For example, many test classes provide
   a "ctxt" attribute, and tests in that class simply need to
   refer to self.ctxt rather than creating another one locally.
2. Context objects are obtained by calling unit test utility
   functions instead of directly instantiating context.RequestContext
   objects. This consolidates where the contexts are created, and
   therefore helps control /how/ they get created.

The new utility functions ensure the contexts contain the appropriate
list of roles, which will allow the unit tests to pass after the
deprecated "owner" rule is removed. Having things consolidated will
also facilitate future changes for secure RBAC, such as when scope
based rules are introduced.

Change-Id: I36e457aa978a968db542e77b15f9b6f4c58677bd

revisions:
[{'created': '2021-09-20 05:57:51.000000000', 'message': 'Sharding: a remote SR without an epoch can't replication over one with an epoch

We've seen this happen a couple of times in production where a root
container suddenly thinks it's unsharded as it's own_shard_range is
reset. The only way this can happen is if a new replica or handoff node
places a container and a new own_shard_range is created and replicated
to older sharded primaries.

This version move the filtering up to the container replicator where we
only deal with OSRs (own_shard_ranges). Looks much cleaner initially,
however it only really works one way. Block remote osr epoch None overwriting
local epoched OSR.
Going the other way, allowing a remote epoched osr overwrite a non
epoched (default) osr. Because a "new default" OSR will hav a newer
timestamp, so one would need to delve into the shard_range table and
hack or delete the default to be older then the remote correct one.

Maybe a third approach is to still do it in the merge_shard_ranges
because it's where we can control all, but change to epoch check to only
hapen if the shard range path == broker path, meaning it's checking
OSRs, and not as global.

Change-Id: I069bdbeb430e89074605e40525d955b3a704a44f
'}, {'created': '2021-09-21 05:49:28.000000000', 'message': "Sharding: a remote SR without an epoch can't replication over one with an epoch

We've seen this happen a couple of times in production where a root
container suddenly thinks it's unsharded as it's own_shard_range is
reset. The only way this can happen is if a new replica or handoff node
places a container and a new own_shard_range is created and replicated
to older sharded primaries.

This version move the filtering up to the container replicator where we
only deal with OSRs (own_shard_ranges). Looks much cleaner initially,
however it only really works one way. Block remote osr epoch None overwriting
local epoched OSR.
Going the other way it much harder. So as this patch stands it
essentially blocks a primary with a good epoched OSR from pulling in a
bad non-epoched OSR from a remote. As a conserquence if the bad nodes
non-epoched OSR is newer then the good one it pulls from it's neighbours
then it'll be left stuck with it's bad one.

When this happens I'd expect to see a bunch of:
    Not merging remote own_shard_range into <broker path>

messages as they'd be stuck. If however, the bad OSR is older than the
good OSR then the bad node pulls a good OSR it'll merge the shard over the
bad one.

Change-Id: I069bdbeb430e89074605e40525d955b3a704a44f

commit_message:
sharding: don't replace own_shard_range without an epoch

We've observed a root container suddenly thinks it's unsharded when it's
own_shard_range is reset.  This patch blocks a remote osr with an epoch
of None from overwriting a local epoched OSR.

The only way we've observed this happen is when a new replica or handoff
node creates a container and it's new own_shard_range is created without
an epoch and then replicated to older primaries.

However, if a bad node with a non-epoched OSR is on a primary, it's
newer timestamp would prevent pulling the good osr from it's peers.  So
it'll be left stuck with it's bad one.

When this happens expect to see a bunch of:
    Ignoring remote osr w/o epoch: x, from: y

These warnings can also be observed, when sharding shards, as
demonstrated by the probetest.

Closes-bug: #1980451
Change-Id: I069bdbeb430e89074605e40525d955b3a704a44f

commit_message:
Delete resource provider after node deletion.

After node deletion resource provider exists for some time.
Time gap can long minutes.
Nove scheduler can schedule on deleted node,
which causes error behavior.
Time gap depends on nova option 'report_interval'.
If we decrease the value the gap is less.
But it increases load in deployment,
especially in high-loaded one.
So the option is not a cure.
The patch removes resource provider in placement after node deletion.
It doesn't solve the problem of nova and ironic synchronization,
but it's "nice thing" which helps.

Story: #1248022
Task: #9332
Change-Id: I352429065eedb1dcbbfa803ec2814c3e870c3be9

commit_message:
Catch exceptions during bootstrap process

Currently the errors in bootstrap process
are guarded and the event is marked as
successful. This patch catch the exceptions
and returns False so that bootstrap state
can be set to False and the event can be
deferred.

Depends-On: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/charm-ops-sunbeam/+/859008
Change-Id: I8ef17118e2a42d71b1a4755dfcbaf923497d1c9a

commit_message:
Capture port deleted event associated to HM ServiceMonitor

When the port associated to a VM is deleted, if a ServiceMonitor
row is associated to that port an OVN SB event is triggered
in order to communicate that the ServiceMonitor entry is been
deleted. That event would allow us to update the status of
member/pool/LB according to the event.

This patch suscribes the driver agent to the DELETE events
for table ServiceMonitor on the OVN SB DB in order to
update the operating_status when the VM port is deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1989460
Change-Id: I9f8c5668c260a896f5c5848734854551c842db1e

commit_message:
Capture port deleted event associated to HM ServiceMonitor

When the port associated to a VM is deleted, if a ServiceMonitor
row is associated to that port an OVN SB event is triggered
in order to communicate that the ServiceMonitor entry is been
deleted. That event would allow us to update the status of
member/pool/LB according to the event.

This patch suscribes the driver agent to the DELETE events
for table ServiceMonitor on the OVN SB DB in order to
update the operating_status when the VM port is deleted.

Closes-Bug: #1989460
Change-Id: I9f8c5668c260a896f5c5848734854551c842db1e
(cherry picked from commit 30db5c88cefd153983c0193cdf250161fd10640c)

commit_message:
Capture port deleted event associated to HM ServiceMonitor

When the port associated to a VM is deleted, if a ServiceMonitor
row is associated to that port an OVN SB event is triggered
in order to communicate that the ServiceMonitor entry is been
deleted. That event would allow us to update the status of
member/pool/LB according to the event.

This patch suscribes the driver agent to the DELETE events
for table ServiceMonitor on the OVN SB DB in order to
update the operating_status when the VM port is deleted.

commit_message:
Database sync between TackerDB and Kubernetes

The patch supports synchronization of Pod information
(Number of Pods, Pod name) between TackerDB and Kubernetes.
If there are differences in the Pod information,
it will synchronize the TackerDB information with the
Kubernetes information.
This process is performed periodically, and its interval
is configurable.

Implements: blueprint database-synchronization
Change-Id: I7bb00d9cc0a6f110a68cdb4ecc2bc10665dcdacc

commit_message:
Add custom seccomp profile for ephemeral heat

This profile is similar to 'unconfined' would allow all
syscalls that cause issues with older podman versions.

Change-Id: Ibc8746762e9d5de2a2ed0afe92b53591c66d00a4
(cherry picked from commit ad6bc22f217929a78ba2a9dada036b176d2717ed)

commit_message:
CI: mark Debian as non-voting due to qemu bug

Due to error in qemu packaging we cannot build working images.
Downgrading qemu would be serious downgrade (7.0 -> 5.2) so we mark
Debian CI jobs as non-voting for now.

To be reverted.

https://bugs.debian.org/cgi-bin/bugreport.cgi?bug=1020776

Change-Id: I2452f0b1b3b835379a1288a226728b3ac63a7cef

commit_message:
Allow role re-tagging of ports

We currently tag ports with 'tripleo_role=<role>' and use
it for inventory generation. This does not help when we want
to move a set of nodes to a different similar role. This change
re-tags the ports with the new role, if there is a change.

Change-Id: I02e9aa5180d8262a6cb69933094526d5dbde8318

commit_message:
Add missing comma in .pylintrc

Without the comma in the deprecated-modules section, any
subsequent arguments are silently ignored. Add it so pylint
will catch any six imports.

Change-Id: I4bca5ab81dd4ef6f28c7ff854dcc782a9b3c3f12

commit_message:
fix: fix octavia request headers

Add accept:application/json to all the octavia requests, to get the return data in json format, otherwise it may get the return data in xml format

Closes-Bug: #1990250

commit_message:
Quota configuration: improve example oslo_limit section

This patch:
- uses "glance" instead of "MY_SERVICE";
- uses the already existing public glance endpoint id rather than
  "ENDPOINT_ID";
- uses the already existing "GLANCE_PASS" rather than introducing
  "MY_PASSWORD".

Closes-Bug: #1990854
Change-Id: I8f5214b879818ec5f1a62d369274ad0d67396b9b

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/zed

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/zed branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ie7f17b44f0dd48a4d20f6d28c8dfa1e12f839d58

commit_message:
Do not reboot into nowhere after BIOS settings with fast-track

Currently, the prepare_ramdisk implementation of the
redfish-virtual-media boot interface skips configuring an ISO in
fast-track mode. When rebooting after BIOS/RAID settings changes, we
need to enforce the correct ISO configuration.

Conflicts:
	ironic/drivers/modules/deploy_utils.py
	ironic/drivers/modules/redfish/bios.py

Change-Id: Ibdfe0775065f3b27478305dd18929a291df3ee3c
(cherry picked from commit 89f421b166915a22626dcb919382ce13f4588973)
(cherry picked from commit d85d7f8ac52f289b7b01096c65757b68791f4bd4)
(cherry picked from commit 66373aadc04974de0838abc43c5f9cf113781f1f)

commit_message:
Workaround qemu query-migrate issue during live migration

There is a possible issue [1] in qemu around the query-migrate command
where if it is called any time after a migration is complete, libvirt
will raise an error:

  libvirt.libvirtError: internal error: migration was active, but no
  RAM info was set

The query-migrate command is indirectly called by the libvirt driver
during live migration monitoring. If there is a race and the driver
attempts to query for migration job info after the migration has
completed, it causes us to fail the migration when it is actually
complete.

We can work around this behavior by catching and ignoring this specific
error and considering the migration complete/successful.

Closes-Bug: #1982284

[1] https://github.com/qemu/qemu/commit/552de79bfdd5e9e53847eb3c6d6e4cd898a4370e

Change-Id: Icacd4440d6b30daac5035ee0f5920b63a728e23f

commit_message:
setup.cfg: Replace dashes by underscores

Since setuptools v54.1.0[1], the parmeters with dash have been
deprecated in favor of the new parameters with underscore.

This change updates the parameters accordingly to avoid the warnings
like the example below.

  UserWarning: Usage of dash-separated 'description-file' will not be
  supported in future versions. Please use the underscore name
  'description_file' instead

[1] https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/commit/a2e9ae4cb

Change-Id: Ica879c31574060471fb22c53761e6d4549a05db2

commit_message:
Fix install of virtualbmc on ussuri (again)

Use git tag rather than commit sha for virtualbmc branch.
Otherwise devstack install fails with:

```
++ functions-common:git_timed:637           :   timeout -s SIGINT 0 git clone https://opendev.org/openstack/virtualbmc.git /opt/stack/virtualbmc --branch 835fd3b9e4cbb33a297e979db93df55498ff6ce0
Cloning into '/opt/stack/virtualbmc'...
fatal: Remote branch 835fd3b9e4cbb33a297e979db93df55498ff6ce0 not found in upstream origin
```

Change-Id: I730ca36bc86632b1d13de6342714ce59ea3c9af3

commit_message:
Improving parameters processing

- parametrize BMC credentials.
- adding ability to set variables from the ENV to avoid sensitive
  data leak to a terminal or process listing.

'required=True' has been removed from the '--instance' parameter
to allow setting it from the ENV.

Change-Id: Ida5df11fc3c50dcdabd2741b9a8abfa5fb87ed45

commit_message:
Build separately for each supported series and use binary builds

Charms for OpenStack Yoga supports both Ubuntu Focal and Jammy
which means Python 3.8 and Python 3.10.  Managing dependencies
across those two versions is non-trivial and we need to build
the charm on the series the charm is supposed to support.

Switch to using a binary build which allows pip's dependency
resolution to work.

This patch also drops the impish bundle.

Change-Id: I0f9797f5efb3716b788e4884cd271d0827c6f10a

If you've got thousands of requests per second for objects in a single

going to overload the container.

Avoid this by allowing some small fraction of requests to bypass and
refresh the cache, pushing out the TTL as long as there continue to be

commit_message:
proxy: Add a chance to skip memcache for get_*_info calls

If you've got thousands of requests per second for objects in a single
container, you basically NEVER want that container's info to ever fall
out of memcache. If it *does*, all those clients are almost certainly
going to overload the container.

Avoid this by allowing some small fraction of requests to bypass and
refresh the cache, pushing out the TTL as long as there continue to be
requests to the container. The likelihood of skipping the cache is
configurable, similar to what we did for shard range sets.

Change-Id: If9249a42b30e2a2e7c4b0b91f947f24bf891b86f

commit_message:
[stable-only] Cap virtualenv for py37

py37 test started to fail with latest virtualenv (20.16.4) as it
bundles setuptools 65.3.0, which causes installation problems under
py37. (Note: with py38 the problem does not occur).

This patch sets virtualenv<20.16.4 to unblock the gate as
virtualenv 20.16.3 bundles setuptools 63.4.1, with which py37 gate
works well.

Conflicts:
  tox.ini

NOTE(elod.illes): conflict is caused by tox.ini cleanup patch, that was
  added in ussuri: I13e72ec6cbd006ca6eccfe21f2a0584e86a52669

Change-Id: I29beb88dd241af72397bf0dd1fc46c98a229425c
(cherry picked from commit 766715d310fb5b9d074b2e34693fa04f585008c9)

commit_message:
Remove unnecessary hacking checks

The B319 check to ensure no use of xrange is not an issue in a Python
3-only codebase, while the unittest assert-focused B311, B312 and B321
checks duplicate H203, H204 and H203 (again) from hacking respectively.

An unnecessary 'py3pep8' tox environment is removed since the standard
'pep8' environment uses Python 3 now.

Change-Id: I8eb8c6accd1c2f2c7851a08b372235699a971ad9
Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>

commit_message:
tox: Minor tweaks

Set the 'PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE' environment variable to avoid
generating '*.pyc' files, allowing us to remove explicit cleanup of
these from some tox environments.

Signed-off-by: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Support K8s 1.24+

Only specify dockershim options when container runtime is not containerd.
Those options were ignored in the past when using containerd but since 1.24
kubelet refuses to start.

Task: 45282
Story: 2010028

Signed-off-by: Daniel Meyerholt <dxm523@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Ib44cc30285c8bd4219d4a45dc956696505ddd570

commit_message:
Update python testing as per zed cycle teting runtime

In Zed cycle, we have dropped the python 3.6/3.7[1] testing
and its support. Removing the py36 centos8 job as well as
updating the python classifier also to reflect the same.

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/reference/runtimes/zed.html

commit_message:
Use "OVNMechDriver" instance in "TestOvn[Nb|Sb]IdlNotifyHandler"

The test classes "TestOvn[Nb|Sb]IdlNotifyHandler" now use the
"OVNMechDriver" instance to create the "OvnNbIdl" instance, that
is stored in "self.mech_driver", instead of "self.driver".

Closes-Bug: #1990374

revisions:
[{'created': '2022-09-26 12:51:34.000000000', 'message': 'Migration revert plan

As a failsave the migration code can create a backup of
the controllers to use in case that the migration fails
and leaves the environment on a unusable state.

The revert plan has two stages:
1- Backup stage: included on the current ovn-migration.yml.
   Can be configured using the env variable CREATE_BACKUP
   (True by default). This stage will run the new ansible
   role, recovery-backup.
   It will store the backup on `/ctl_plane_backup` on the host
   where the BACKUP_MIGRATION_IP belongs to (can be modified by
   modifing the env var).
   In order to restore the controllers, boot them using the iso created
   by ReaR (stored in /ctl_plane_backup) and perform `automatic recover`
2- Revert stage: this stage has its own ansible playbook (revert.yml)
   This playbook will clean the environment from all the OVN ressources
   that could had been created (breaking the data plane connectivity)
   to leave the environment in a stage where an overcloud deploy with
   the OVS templates can be run.

Note: If the user creates new resources after running the backup stage
and then performs the recovery of the controllers, those resources will
be lost.

Change-Id: I7093f6a5f282b06fb2267cf2c88c533c1eae685d
(cherry picked from commit 7003817b697beae2f5effd96a3f71d2c2787e64f)
'}]
commit_message:
Migration revert plan

As a failsave the migration code can create a backup of
the controllers to use in case that the migration fails
and leaves the environment on a unusable state.

The revert plan has two stages:
1- Backup stage: included on the current ovn-migration.yml.
   Can be configured using the env variable CREATE_BACKUP
   (True by default). This stage will run the new ansible
   role, recovery-backup.
   It will store the backup on `/ctl_plane_backup` on the host
   where the BACKUP_MIGRATION_IP belongs to (can be modified by
   modifing the env var).
   In order to restore the controllers, boot them using the iso created
   by ReaR (stored in /ctl_plane_backup) and perform `automatic recover`
2- Revert stage: this stage has its own ansible playbook (revert.yml)
   This playbook will clean the environment from all the OVN ressources
   that could had been created (breaking the data plane connectivity)
   to leave the environment in a stage where an overcloud deploy with
   the OVS templates can be run.

Note: If the user creates new resources after running the backup stage
and then performs the recovery of the controllers, those resources will
be lost.

Change-Id: I7093f6a5f282b06fb2267cf2c88c533c1eae685d
(cherry picked from commit 7003817b697beae2f5effd96a3f71d2c2787e64f)

commit_message:
Neutron needs oslo.config >= 9

Building the Neutron package in Debian unstable fails,
because oslo.config 8.8.0 isn't enough. Adding a depends
on python3-oslo.config (>= 9.0.0), available from Debian
experimental, fixed my build. Please adopt this fix in
upstream Neutron.

Change-Id: Ibe2892e12b90d2e6d457e70f2a47a44972ec6193

commit_message:
Dell PowerStore: Add test for NVMEoF Adapter

This patch adds tests for the NVMEoF Adapter testing the following
methods:

1) _get_nvme_targets - 2 tests
2) _get_connection_properties - 1 test

This is a followup requested on [1]. Since no tests existed, it was
better to add tests for the whole class rather than just covering one
method and is a separate effort from [1].

[1] https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/cinder/+/852261

Change-Id: I0de20655ddfaeeceb15d53337c3e9be644f06b21

commit_message:
Disable conntrack for TCP flows in the amphora

conntrack is used in the amphora for LVS-based listeners (UDP and
SCTP) and it's enabled by default.
Add nft/iptable rules to disable conntrack for TCP flows, it reduces
memory usage and prevents getting "nf_conntrack: table full, dropping
packet" messages.

Story: 2008979
Task: 42623

Note for stable/ussuri: this is not a straighforward backport but a
reimplementation of the bugfix for old branches.

Change-Id: Ia15a110c6c5a9b83a29bab56538fa425d994d477
(cherry picked from commit b3f59eeb73289306dd5fd2e9d664903911dc614c)
(cherry picked from commit 1905859662a75403705db2fca6619b929814fc6d)
(cherry picked from commit c0ad3b347d514d6851c1c9234af0dc2d5c2a6952)

commit_message:
[CS8][Wallaby] Exclude container-selinux-2:2.189.0

Latest version of udica[1] requires container-selinux.
In ffu upgrade job, during container-selinux installation,
It gives following error:
```
package container-selinux-2:2.189.0-1.module_el8.7.0+1217+ea57d1f1.noarch
conflicts with udica < 0.2.6-1 provided by udica-0.2.4-1.module_el8.7.0+1217+ea57d1f1.noarch
```
Excluding latest container-selinux-2:2.189.0 fixes the issue
as it works with existing udica-0.2.4-1.module_el8.

[1]. https://koji.mbox.centos.org/koji/buildinfo?buildID=22871

Related-Bug: #1990810

Signed-off-by: Chandan Kumar (raukadah) <chkumar@redhat.com>
Change-Id: Ied21dbba59dbfe174036d2301ab9543c924c1de5

commit_message:
setup.cfg: Replace dashes by underscores

Since setuptools v54.1.0[1], the parmeters with dash have been
deprecated in favor of the new parameters with underscore.

This change updates the parameters accordingly to avoid the warnings
like the example below.

  UserWarning: Usage of dash-separated 'description-file' will not be
  supported in future versions. Please use the underscore name
  'description_file' instead

[1] https://github.com/pypa/setuptools/commit/a2e9ae4cb

commit_message:
Add cephfs_nfs_cluster_id option

As part of change I1826f2970528928a31b32a664013380e38bbd7c9
we added a configuration option to the manila cephfs nfs driver
when deployed using cephadm.

We also need this option set here to get the m-shr service
to pick the right helper when deploying with DevStack

commit_message:
Remove deprecated sysctl knobs

Kolla Ansible stopped setting them as they turned out to be
unnecessary for its operations, yet may have conflicted with
security policies of the hosts. [1] [2]

[1] https://launchpad.net/bugs/1837551
[2] https://launchpad.net/bugs/1945453

Change-Id: Ie8ccd3ab6f22a6f548b1da8d3acd334068dc48f5

commit_message:
Release neutron-tempest-plugin for Zed

This patch proposes a release for neutron-tempest-plugin
to get the latest merged changes out prior to the final Zed going
into effect.

If the team is ready to proceed, please leave a +1 to acknowledge this
release and we will process right away. If the team is working on any
final merges, leave a -1 with some detail on the status and update the
patch with the new commit hash to use when ready.

Patches with no response will be merged by early Friday, September 23.

Signed-off-by: Elod Illes <elod.illes@est.tech>
Change-Id: I6686756889dc71ae07683c169aa3094c66dc5e6b

commit_message:
Get OVS assignment right

As reported in the linked bug, the OVS role has issues with actual
placement. This patch gets it right. It avoids the use of static
inventory entirely and is backwards compatible. Only correct hosts
will now have the OVS logic applied.

Closes-Bug: #1971488
Change-Id: Ie92b6a27a656491601606b76e410e247f82b46b1

subject: [CI] Change the Zun scenario to altcomp scenario
revisions:
[{'created': '2022-07-27 10:10:50.000000000', 'message': '[CI] Change the Zun scenario to altcomp scenario

As discussed some time ago, we prefer to have the altcomp scenario
which covers other ways to deploy the compute. This would normally
include also Zun but now it is being removed due to the decline
in activity as well as it being broken on multiple fronts. [1] [2]

At the moment, the scenario runs multinode compute with Cinder
LVM-backed volumes. This is our only scenario to test non-Ceph
Cinder (which is best to validate if only Ceph is affected).
In the future, this may (and likely will) include the deployment
of additional services, like Blazar.

Glossary

altcomp = alternative compute

[1] https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/zun/+/851196
[2] https://bugs.launchpad.net/zun/+bug/1982924

commit_message:
[CI] Change the Zun scenario to altcomp scenario

As discussed some time ago, we prefer to have the alternative
compute (altcomp) scenario which covers other ways to deploy
the compute plane.
The scenario keeps Zun but the new name reinforces the fact
that this scenario is testing more than Zun.

At the moment, the scenario runs multinode compute with Cinder
LVM-backed volumes. This is our only scenario to test non-Ceph
Cinder (which is best to validate if only Ceph is affected).
In the future, this may (and likely will) include the deployment
of additional services, like Blazar, similarly to how Zun is
included currently.

Change-Id: I2651be1b5073b3395e47e8d0de1b540cb6d17457

commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/zed

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/zed branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: Ia4c4432aa444a0bbac9ac69c991011353a347623

commit_message:
Fix compatibility with oslo.db 12.1.0

oslo.db 12.1.0 has changed the default value for the 'autocommit'
parameter of 'LegacyEngineFacade' from 'True' to 'False'. This is a
necessary step to ensure compatibility with SQLAlchemy 2.0. However, we
are currently relying on the autocommit behavior and need changes to
explicitly manage sessions. Until that happens, we need to override the
default.

Also squashed change: [CI] move queue setting to project level

Jobs are currently not running. Fix as described in [1][2]

[1] https://lists.opendev.org/pipermail/service-announce/2022-September/000044.html
[2] https://lists.zuul-ci.org/pipermail/zuul-discuss/2022-May/001801.html

Story: 2010296
Co-Authored-By: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Jake Yip <jake.yip@ardc.edu.au>
Change-Id: I625500d9e6670a429c70a0f6d582d0865ce78fd1
(cherry picked from commit fd6f2d52386036cc652d59b43c9aba9efe962950)

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/zed branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

'}]
commit_message:
Update TOX_CONSTRAINTS_FILE for stable/zed

Update the URL to the upper-constraints file to point to the redirect
rule on releases.openstack.org so that anyone working on this branch
will switch to the correct upper-constraints list automatically when
the requirements repository branches.

Until the requirements repository has as stable/zed branch, tests will
continue to use the upper-constraints list on master.

Change-Id: I2dc238245aa7eac2d8e884b1104f98298d054211

commit_message:
puppet: Test pacemaker services by multinode ipa job

This change adds a few more triggers to multinode-ipa job so that we
test the scenario for the change with puppet-tripleo change related to
the core pacemaker services(haproxy, galera and rabbitmq).

Change-Id: I85803861228c0038b4cfe1867cd273088d2b48f7

While scanning for the devices, we rely on the H:B:T:L values (SCSI address)
where host(H) and bus(B) are the kernel assigned values on the host but
the target and LUN are on the storage array side.
We get the LUN ID (while mapping the volume through cinder) in the
connection information but we are not aware about the target ID.

commit_message:
WIP: Don't use specific target ID during FC scan

While scanning for the devices, we rely on the H:B:T:L values (SCSI address)
where host(H) and bus(B) are the kernel assigned values on the host but
the target and LUN are on the storage array side.
We get the LUN ID (while mapping the volume through cinder) in the
connection information but we are not aware about the target ID.

We try to use existing target IDs (from past mapped devices) fetched
from the "/sys/class/fc_transport/targetH:B:T/port_name" path but
they only contain targets from the storage array we've mapped before.
If we try to map a LUN from a new storage array, we run into the error
NoFibreChannelVolumeDeviceFound since the new target IDs are not known.

This patch replaces the target ID with a wildcard during scan.

Change-Id: I4063737b2a5b6a207f739b944a43b86564054f0b

commit_message:
Fix compatibility with oslo.db 12.1.0

oslo.db 12.1.0 has changed the default value for the 'autocommit'
parameter of 'LegacyEngineFacade' from 'True' to 'False'. This is a
necessary step to ensure compatibility with SQLAlchemy 2.0. However, we
are currently relying on the autocommit behavior and need changes to
explicitly manage sessions. Until that happens, we need to override the
default.

This also moves the watcher queue declaration from the pipeline level
(where it is no longer valid) to the project level.

Co-Authored-By: Thierry Carrez <thierry@openstack.org>
Co-Authored-By: Stephen Finucane <stephenfin@redhat.com>
(cherry picked from commit 5d70c207cddbaedceba6e1e6e9ae89bbd851aacc)
Change-Id: I7db39d958d087322bfa0aad70dfbd04de9228dd7

commit_message:
Charmhub migration for stable/train (bionic-only)

This is the main patch for the migration of the stable/21.10
charm to charmhub for the stable/train branch (train track on
charmhub).  This patch initially supports bionic from queens
to train, and does not support ussuri.  It supports upgrades
from bionic-queens to bionic-train (with each intermediate
step needed).  Crucially it does NOT set a default
openstack-origin, which means installing train/stable
without specifying the openstack-origin will result in a
bionic-queens installation.  This is intentional as the branch
covers queens to train.

Disable Rockcy deferred restarts tests as the restart causes
connetivity issues due to https://bugs.launchpad.net/cloud-archive/+bug/1990264

Change-Id: Iad93f7e974823e66e14e9bf51dce38a53664c90f

commit_message:
Support role specific ContainerImagePrepare

This is the last change of the series of changes to implements partial
support for overriding the ContainerImaePrepare parameter for
individual roles, so that users can use different set of images for
each role.

example:
parameter_defaults:
  ContainerImagePrepare:
    - push_destination: true
      set:
        name_prefix: openstack-
        name_suffix: ''
        namespace: quay.io/repository/tripleowallabycentos9
        ...
  ComputeEl8ContainerImagePrepare:
    - push_destination: true
      set:
        name_prefix: openstack-
        name_suffix: ''
        namespace: quay.io/repository/tripleowallabycentos8
        ...

This change makes the deployment command to generate the image
parameters in tht according to these layered definitions.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/851690
Change-Id: I76f78a12f6b4b0763a47e85f38f743da6269a47e

[{'created': '2019-09-17 03:18:05.000000000', 'message': "[train][goal] Define new ec2-api-functional-neutron-ipv6-only job

As part of Train community goal 'Support IPv6-Only Deployments and Testing'[1],
we need to define the integration job which deploy services
on IPv6 and perform testing to make sure service listen and communicate
over IPv6 properly.

ec2-api has legacy zuul jobs only so base zuulv3 IPv6 job 'devstack-ipv6' and
'devstack-tempest-ipv6' cannot be used and we have to copy the whole
run.yaml to set the IPv6 setting and run the IPv6 verification
script via post_test_hook.

This commit adds the new job 'ec2-api-functional-neutron-ipv6-only'
run on gate and set the required IPv6 setting'.

Story: #2005477
Task: #35889

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/train/ipv6-support-and-testing.html

commit_message:
[train][goal] Define new ec2-api-functional-neutron-ipv6-only job

As part of Train community goal 'Support IPv6-Only Deployments and Testing'[1],
we need to define the integration job which deploy services
on IPv6 and perform testing to make sure service listen and communicate
over IPv6 properly.

ec2-api has legacy zuul jobs only so base zuulv3 IPv6 job 'devstack-ipv6' and
'devstack-tempest-ipv6' cannot be used and we have to copy the whole
run.yaml to set the IPv6 setting and run the IPv6 verification
script via post_test_hook.

This commit adds the new job 'ec2-api-functional-neutron-ipv6-only'
run on gate and set the required IPv6 setting'.

Story: #2005477
Task: #35889

[1] https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/train/ipv6-support-and-testing.html

Depends-On: Id00db3f303f45daf0e25be1f1bcf6a8834cb3ea7
Change-Id: I9b7048469a6eff8b5f5b0cc439dea58f761a75bb

New releases of oslo.config support a 'mutable' parameter to Opts.
oslo.service provides an option here Icec3e664f3fe72614e373b2938e8dee53cf8bc5e
allows services to tell oslo.service they want mutate_config_files to be

This commit is to use the same. This allows ec2api to benefit from

commit_message:
Enable mutable config in ec2api

New releases of oslo.config support a 'mutable' parameter to Opts.
oslo.service provides an option here Icec3e664f3fe72614e373b2938e8dee53cf8bc5e
allows services to tell oslo.service they want mutate_config_files to be
called by passing a parameter.

This commit is to use the same. This allows ec2api to benefit from
I1e7a69de169cc85f4c09954b2f46ce2da7106d90, where the 'debug' option
(owned by oslo.log) is made mutable. we should be able to turn debug
logging on and off by changing the config.

tc goal:
https://governance.openstack.org/tc/goals/rocky/enable-mutable-configuration.html

Change-Id: Id6b0d9d25cd8ad346fbf3bd90c6dbe568600912e

commit_message:
Support role specific ContainerImagePrepare

This implements partial support for overriding the ContainerImaePrepare
parameter for individual roles, so that users can use different set
of images for each role.

example:
parameter_defaults:
  ContainerImagePrepare:
    - push_destination: true
      set:
        name_prefix: openstack-
        name_suffix: ''
        namespace: quay.io/repository/tripleowallabycentos9
        ...
  ComputeEl8ContainerImagePrepare:
    - push_destination: true
      set:
        name_prefix: openstack-
        name_suffix: ''
        namespace: quay.io/repository/tripleowallabycentos8
        ...

This change ensures that container image prepare process, which is
executed by external tasks, pulls container images according to these
layer definitions so that the required container images are downloaded
and pushed to the undercloud image-server during deployment.

Depends-on: https://review.opendev.org/c/openstack/tripleo-ansible/+/851689
Change-Id: I7c96d7d0f23fd999e76b417f456ac6a2764c4a3e

commit_message:
Move zuulv3 jobs to project repo

This patch moves the zuulv3 jobs for ec2-api repo.

This is first step to switch jobs to ec2 tempest plugin.

There is already gate broken due to switching neutron_vpnaas
to neutron-tempest-plugin whichy stop any further updates to merge
in ec2-api repo.
This commit also fix that.

To make this merge, legacy job needs to be remopved first. Done in below
dependent patch:
Depends-On: I0e5a1c37b407497fd9e60e58bac7c7a89e14dc75

Needed-By: I0c342072f7d749b0243889e2bedd636347df23ef

Change-Id: I9c88ac1ecf0368c9ea7a8b20c84995ea29487184
(cherry picked from commit 6dcaa64626b48447b8d84eac63a91a2ef8098707)

commit_message:
Support role specific ContainerImagePrepare

This implements partial support for overriding the ContainerImaePrepare
parameter for individual roles, so that users can use different set
of images for each role.

example:
parameter_defaults:
  ContainerImagePrepare:
    - push_destination: true
      set:
        name_prefix: openstack-
        name_suffix: ''
        namespace: quay.io/repository/tripleowallabycentos9
        ...
  ComputeEl8ContainerImagePrepare:
    - push_destination: true
      set:
        name_prefix: openstack-
        name_suffix: ''
        namespace: quay.io/repository/tripleowallabycentos8
        ...

Change-Id: I3209688eabfdb507f924f86c55ebbf6526ce7ef7
